subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis
.

— Carapace narrowing to posterior, straight borders with gentle cleft, corresponding to second anterolateral tooth (
Fig. 2c
). Male chela characterised by presence of a double line of weak tubercles along inner palm surface (

Fig. 
3g

), with palm height 1.70 (± 0.12; n = 6) times maximum chelar width. Descending slope of palm (with parallel prominent ridge) at articulation with dactylus almost transverse (
Fig. 3c
). Lower margin of chela convex. Dorsal surface of dactylus covered with tubercles until tip (
Fig. 4c, g
). Male abdomen relatively more quadrate; somite 6 with proximal width 1.13 (± 0.093; n = 6) times length; telson length 1.09 (± 0.11; n = 6) times width (
Fig. 5c
).
